Beneventum] The Appia Via took a north-east turn from Caudium for ten miles till it came to Beneventum (Bene- vento), a very ancient town, by tradition said to have been founded by Diomed, and the name of which was originally, when the Samnites had it, Maleventum, or some name that sounded so like Maleventum to a Latin ear that the Romans thought fit to change it (for good luck) to Beneventum. In no town but Rome are there so many remains of ancient art found as in Benevento. Nearly all the walls are built os altars, tombs, columns, διας and the arch of Trajan, erec- ted probably in commemorationi of his con- struction of the read from Beneventum to Brundusium (since the same year, Aa). 114, appears on the arch that is found on the milliary columns along the road), still re- mains in pretty good preservation. Thither the party proceeded next day, and put up at an inu, when the host nearly set fire to his house through carelessness in roasting some indifferent thrushes for their dinner. ⁴ Hospes paene arsit,’ the host nearly got himself on fire, means that he nearly burnt the house down, as the context shows.
